Module 8: Structures & Unions

This is an important interview topic because it tests your understanding of how C stores and organizes data.

What is a Structure?

A structure is a user-defined data type that allows us to store different types of data together under one name.

Why do we need a Structure?

Suppose you want to store student information.

Without a structure:

char name[20];
int roll;
float marks;

For 100 students, you'll need separate arrays and it becomes difficult to manage.

Using a structure:

struct Student
{
    char name[20];
    int roll;
    float marks;
};

Now all information related to one student is grouped together.

Creating a Structure Variable
struct Student s1;

Access members:

s1.roll = 101;
s1.marks = 89.5;

. is called the member access operator.

Structure in Memory
struct Student
{
    int roll;
    float marks;
    char grade;
};

Memory:

+--------+---------+-------+
| roll   | marks   | grade |
+--------+---------+-------+

Each member gets its own memory.

Array of Structures
struct Student s[100];

Stores data of 100 students.

Pointer to Structure
struct Student s1;

struct Student *ptr = &s1;

Access members using:

ptr->roll = 101;

Instead of

(*ptr).roll = 101;

-> is called the arrow operator.

Structure Padding

Suppose:

struct Test
{
    char a;
    int b;
};

Many students think:

1 + 4 = 5 bytes

But actually it is often 8 bytes.

Why?

The compiler adds padding for faster memory access.

Memory:

char
padding padding padding
int
Why Padding?

CPUs access aligned memory faster.

Padding improves performance.

sizeof(Structure)

Example:

struct Test
{
    char a;
    int b;
};

printf("%lu", sizeof(struct Test));

Output may be:

8

Not 5.

What is a Union?

A union is also a user-defined data type.

Difference:

All members share the same memory location.

Example:

union Data
{
    int a;
    float b;
    char c;
};

Memory:

+-----------+
| Shared    |
| Memory    |
+-----------+

Only one member can store a meaningful value at a time.

Example
union Data d;

d.a = 10;
d.b = 5.5;

Now d.a is overwritten.

Only the latest value remains valid.

Structure vs Union
Structure	Union
Separate memory for each member	Shared memory
All members can store values together	Only one member is valid at a time
Memory = sum of member sizes (plus padding)	Memory = size of the largest member
When do we use Structures?
Student records
Employee details
Bank accounts
Product information
When do we use Unions?
Memory optimization
Embedded systems
Hardware programming
Device drivers
Important Interview Questions (Module 8)
1. What is a structure?

Answer: A user-defined data type that groups variables of different data types under one name.

2. Why do we use structures?

To store related data as a single unit.

3. What is a union?

A user-defined data type where all members share the same memory.

4. Difference between Structure and Union?
Structure	Union
Separate memory	Shared memory
All values exist together	One value at a time
5. Why is a union smaller than a structure?

Because all members share the same memory.

6. What is structure padding?

Extra bytes added by the compiler for proper memory alignment and faster access.

7. What is the arrow (->) operator?

Used to access structure members through a pointer.

8. Difference between . and ->?
. → Structure variable
-> → Structure pointer
Module 9: Storage Classes

Storage classes define:

Scope (Where can it be accessed?)
Lifetime (How long does it exist?)
Storage location

There are four storage classes:

auto
static
extern
register
1. auto

Default storage class for local variables.

Example:

void fun()
{
    auto int x = 10;
}

or simply:

int x = 10;

Both are the same.

Scope

Inside the function only.

Lifetime

Until the function returns.

2. static

A static variable is initialized only once.

It keeps its value between function calls.

Example:

#include <stdio.h>

void fun()
{
    static int x = 0;
    x++;
    printf("%d\n", x);
}

int main()
{
    fun();
    fun();
    fun();
}

Output:

1
2
3

Normal local variable:

1
1
1
Why?

Because a static variable is stored in the Data/BSS segment, not on the stack.

3. extern

Suppose:

File1.c

int count = 10;

File2.c

extern int count;

extern tells the compiler:

"This variable exists in another file."

4. register

Requests that the compiler store a variable in a CPU register for faster access.

Example:

register int i;

Today, modern compilers decide automatically, so register is rarely used.

Scope vs Lifetime
Scope

Where a variable can be accessed.

Example:

void fun()
{
    int x;
}

x is only accessible inside fun().

Lifetime

How long the variable exists.

Local variable:

Created when the function starts.

Destroyed when the function ends.

Static variable:

Created once.

Destroyed when the program ends.

Local vs Global Variable
Local	Global
Inside function	Outside function
Stack	Data/BSS
Function scope	Entire file/program
Important Interview Questions (Module 9)
1. What is a storage class?

Answer: A storage class defines a variable's scope, lifetime, and storage location.

2. Name the storage classes.
auto
static
extern
register
3. Difference between Scope and Lifetime?
Scope	Lifetime
Where the variable can be accessed	How long the variable exists
4. Difference between Local and Global Variable?
Local: Declared inside a function, stored on the stack.
Global: Declared outside all functions, stored in the Data or BSS segment.
5. Difference between auto and static?
auto	static
New variable each function call	One variable for the entire program
Stored on stack	Stored in Data/BSS
Value is lost after function returns	Value is preserved
6. Why do we use static?

To retain the value of a variable between function calls.

7. What is extern?

It allows a variable defined in one source file to be used in another source file.

8. What is register?

It suggests storing a variable in a CPU register for faster access, although modern compilers usually ignore the suggestion and optimize automatically.
